Hmm, riddle me this, if you were teleported to a dangerous and primitive world filled with fantastical wonders and buxom anthro babes but were restored to your biological prime, brought to a /fit/ human average where deficient in any area, and given supernatural power over a mixture of the archetypical elements in compensation- to summon, control, and bind said mixture with potential to grow to tremendous heights with practice and effort, which mixture of the elements would you choose and more importantly, how would you use it to score?

For reference, the choices are as follows and have the same overall power and versatility, but hold their own strengths and weaknesses.
>Fire+Earth= Glass
>Fire+Water= Steam
>Fire+Air = Smoke
>Earth+Fire= Magma
>Earth+Water= Mud
>Earth+Air= Dust
>Water+Earth= Ooze
>Water+Air= Frost
>Water+Fire= Naphtha
>Air+Fire= Lightning
>Air+Earth= Pressure
>Air+Water= Mist
In this world, some bigbrains are capable of magic by brute-forcing the substance of creation or aligning their souls to a fundamental element, but your type of mixed magic is extremely rare and so innate to your soul that it can't be separated from you any more easily than your cardiovascular system can. The tech-level is around the early iron age but there's some gonzo tech in ancient ruins that you can't be sure are magic or technology, or some combination of both. The land is crawling with monsters, brigands, and all sorts of other dangers but deep in civilized lands, patrols are regular enough that travel isn't severely dangerous. There's an extremely wide range of anthro species and some discrimination between them, though humans are from several other dimensions, rare enough here that most seasoned travelers go their entire lives without seeing one, and the overwhelming majority of the rumors surrounding them relate to their reckless bravado, limitless stamina, and sexual prowess.

I was thinking the other day that if there were four elements, and said elements were capable of being combined with the three others in two different ways- those being with the emphasis on one or the other, then there would be twelve different combinations, and that would be a neat expansion from the generic elemental thing. You guys are generally smarter than /tg/ and I thought, anon thrown in the middle with hyper-specific but broadly versatile magic, was a fun prompt. >>46438651
Okay, thanks for the long and detailed explanation of why.

>>46441772
It means that you mentally insert yourself into the role of the character, not that you literally think you're the same person. Inserting yourself into the role is easier if the character makes mistakes, because you (as the reader) believe you could fit into the role better. E.g. "If I were Leo, I'd treat Missy better" - you've self-inserted into Leo's role, and think you'd be better at it, but you haven't started thinking like Leo. If Leo is too virtuous then you can't imagine yourself doing better and it paradoxically becomes harder to self-insert into the role, because the role becomes defined by Leo's strong and virtuous character.
